{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778981194225,"sessionID":"ses_1cc754bd9ffeuD9IYi2ivYftXO","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_TFC8709GJPbb04YQ7y0cAR6G","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/__issue_context__.json","offset":1,"limit":400},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/__issue_context__.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"body\": \"* **GO term ID and label for which you request a new superclass**\\n\\nGO:0072318  clathrin coat disassembly\\nThe disaggregation of a clathrin coat into its constituent components; results in stripping or removing the clathrin coat from clathrin-coated vesicles (CCV) before fusing with their targets. CVVs transport cargo from plasma membrane and trans-Golgi to the endosomal system. \\n\\n\\n* **New superclass (parent) suggested**\\n\\nGO:0072583  clathrin-dependent endocytosis\\n\\n* **Reference(s), if appropriate**\\n\",\n3:   \"comments\": [\n4:     {\n5:       \"id\": \"IC_kwDOAkAHws8AAAABAkYeVw\",\n6:       \"author\": {\n7:         \"login\": \"ValWood\"\n8:       },\n9:       \"authorAssociation\": \"MEMBER\",\n10:       \"body\": \"@dragon-ai-agent please add the missing superclass and term tracker ID\",\n11:       \"createdAt\": \"2026-04-28T07:14:08Z\",\n12:       \"includesCreatedEdit\": false,\n13:       \"isMinimized\": false,\n14:       \"minimizedReason\": \"\",\n15:       \"reactionGroups\": [\n16:         {\n17:           \"content\": \"EYES\",\n18:           \"users\": {\n19:             \"totalCount\": 1\n20:           }\n21:         }\n22:       ],\n23:       \"url\": \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31981#issuecomment-4333117015\",\n24:       \"viewerDidAuthor\": false\n25:     },\n26:     {\n27:       \"id\": \"IC_kwDOAkAHws8AAAABAkYmbQ\",\n28:       \"author\": {\n29:         \"login\": \"dragon-ai-agent\"\n30:       },\n31:       \"authorAssociation\": \"MEMBER\",\n32:       \"body\": \"🤖 Working on it...\\n\\nFollow along: [View workflow run](https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/actions/runs/25039245202)\\n\\n*— @dragon-ai-agent*\",\n33:       \"createdAt\": \"2026-04-28T07:14:30Z\",\n34:       \"includesCreatedEdit\": false,\n35:       \"isMinimized\": false,\n36:       \"minimizedReason\": \"\",\n37:       \"reactionGroups\": [],\n38:       \"url\": \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31981#issuecomment-4333119085\",\n39:       \"viewerDidAuthor\": false\n40:     },\n41:     {\n42:       \"id\": \"IC_kwDOAkAHws8AAAABAkaUwg\",\n43:       \"author\": {\n44:         \"login\": \"pgaudet\"\n45:       },\n46:       \"authorAssociation\": \"MEMBER\",\n47:       \"body\": \"This should be part_of, right ? \",\n48:       \"createdAt\": \"2026-04-28T07:19:36Z\",\n49:       \"includesCreatedEdit\": false,\n50:       \"isMinimized\": false,\n51:       \"minimizedReason\": \"\",\n52:       \"reactionGroups\": [\n53:         {\n54:           \"content\": \"THUMBS_UP\",\n55:           \"users\": {\n56:             \"totalCount\": 1\n57:           }\n58:         }\n59:       ],\n60:       \"url\": \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31981#issuecomment-4333147330\",\n61:       \"viewerDidAuthor\": false\n62:     }\n63:   ],\n64:   \"title\": \"Missing parent: GO:0072318  clathrin coat disassembly\",\n65:   \"url\": \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31981\"\n66: }\n\n(End of file - total 66 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"body\": \"* **GO term ID and label for which you request a new superclass**\\n\\nGO:0072318  clathrin coat disassembly\\nThe disaggregation of a clathrin coat into its constituent components; results in stripping or removing the clathrin coat from clathrin-coated vesicles (CCV) before fusing with their targets. CVVs transport cargo from plasma membrane and trans-Golgi to the endosomal system. \\n\\n\\n* **New superclass (parent) suggested**\\n\\nGO:0072583  clathrin-dependent endocytosis\\n\\n* **Reference(s), if appropriate**\\n\",\n  \"comments\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"IC_kwDOAkAHws8AAAABAkYeVw\",\n      \"author\": {\n        \"login\": \"ValWood\"\n      },\n      \"authorAssociation\": \"MEMBER\",\n      \"body\": \"@dragon-ai-agent please add the missing superclass and term tracker ID\",\n      \"createdAt\": \"2026-04-28T07:14:08Z\",\n      \"includesCreatedEdit\": false,\n      \"isMinimized\": false,\n      \"minimizedReason\": \"\",\n      \"reactionGroups\": [\n        {\n          \"content\": \"EYES\",\n          \"users\": {\n            \"totalCount\": 1\n          }","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"__issue_context__.json","time":{"start":1778981194166,"end":1778981194222}},"id":"prt_e338ac9a8001gisvsM5UGFCy5T","sessionID":"ses_1cc754bd9ffeuD9IYi2ivYftXO","messageID":"msg_e338ab55e001VVqszbXzDZNc9l"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778981194250,"sessionID":"ses_1cc754bd9ffeuD9IYi2ivYftXO","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"glob","callID":"call_veUAwFGUpoVhrTgr0xsY7bOD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"**/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md","path":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go"},"output":"No files found","metadata":{"count":0,"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1778981194184,"end":1778981194232}},"id":"prt_e338ac9c0001Iq78lpywqvie1A","sessionID":"ses_1cc754bd9ffeuD9IYi2ivYftXO","messageID":"msg_e338ab55e001VVqszbXzDZNc9l"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778981194250,"sessionID":"ses_1cc754bd9ffeuD9IYi2ivYftXO","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_5LPhQ1Ymevv9qtMm0vjw2DLw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/AGENTS.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/AGENTS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # GO Ontology Project Guide\n2: \n3: This includes instructions for editing the go ontology and related files in response to GitHub issues.\n4: \n5: ## Project Layout\n6: \n7: The project follows standard ODK layout:\n8: \n9:  * src\n10:     * ontology/\n11:        * go-edit.obo\n12:        * Makefile\n13:        * ...\n14:     * taxon_constraints/\n15:        * only_in_taxon.tsv\n16:        * never_in_taxon.tsv\n17:  * terms/   ## checked out copies, for editing\n18:     * GO_NNNNNNN.obo # checked out local copy\n19:  * .claude/\n20:     * skills/   ## specific skill instructions\n21: \n22:  For make targets, a standard pattern is `cd src/ontology && make <TARGET>`. Beware of accidentally changing to the `src/ontology`\n23:  dir and forgetting where you are. It is best to run things from the top level\n24: \n25: These instructions are optimized for claude code. Skills are used, and defined\n26: in `.claude/skills/`\n27: \n28: ## PLAN: Analyze Issue, Plan Approach, and create a TODO/checklist\n29: \n30: Read the entire issue and all associated comments. Be aware that some issues may have auxhiliary discussions, your must first infer the\n31: intent of the requesters and how to satisfy this in a way that conforms to best practice in the ontology. If the user intent from the\n32: issue is hopelessly ambiguous, then write a note asking for clarification in the original issue (using `gh`) and end here.\n33: \n34: Create a plan for addressing the issue. The plan MUST have the following components (you can have more components depending on the nature of the issue)\n35: \n36: - [ ] PLAN: The issue and all its context has been analyzed, the intent is clear, and a plan for addressing it has been created\n37: - [ ] PRE-VALIDATION: Current state of the ontology validates prior to any changes (if not, we can't validate our changes)\n38: - [ ] RESEARCH: If appropriate, necessary background research performed; always use /research for this, it produces a RESEARCH.md file\n39: - [ ] TERM-SEARCH: Relevant ontology terms (this ontology or others) have been consulted\n40: - [ ] DESIGN-PATTERNS: Existing design patterns, terms, and documentation consulted; always use /design-pattern for this, which produces a DESIGN_PATTERNS.md doc\n41: - [ ] EDITS: correct procedure is followed for making edits, using checkin/checkout commands, and local `./terms/ folder\n42: - [ ] RELATIONSHIPS: appropriate relationships and logical axioms are included\n43:     - [ ] logical definitions are appropriate, and are not over-specified, and conform to DESIGN_PATTERNS.md doc\n44:     - [ ] relationships conform to other similar terms in the ontology\n45:     - [ ] is_a is not over-asserted\n46:     - [ ] is_a, part_of, and other relationships specified appropriately\n47: - [ ] SPECIALIZED-EDITS: include checklists from the following skills as appropriate, depending on the nature of the request\n48:     - /term-obsoletion skill; MUST be used for anything involving obsoletion/deprecation of terms\n49:     - /chemical-entity skill; for any request involving CHEBI or chemical terms or nomenclature\n50:     - /reaction skill; for any request involving RHEA, EC, or the catalytic activity branch of GO\n51:     - /taxon-constraint skill; for any request involving restricting usage of a term or branch to a taxon/clade\n52: - [ ] METADATA: The metadata for the changes is correct\n53: - [ ] AUTOMATED-VALIDATION: The ontology validates correctly using `make travis_build` after changes have been made\n54: - [ ] REFERENCE-VALIDATION: All references (eg PMIDs) introduced have been validated, and are relevant, and not typos or hallucinations; always use /research for this\n55: - [ ] CHANGES-COMMITTED\n56:     - [ ] RELEVANT-FILES: changes to src/ontology/go-edit.obo and any other content file are committed with detailed messages and signatures\n57:     - [ ] ACCURACY: The changes made are biologically correct, accurate, and reasonably complete; always use /research to obtain background material\n58:     - [ ] ISSUE-ALIGNMENT: The changes made are in accordance with the issue request and forms a coherent unit of work;\n59:     - [ ] PR is created or amended\n60:     - [ ] Communicate high level summary of changes on original issue(s), and any requests for further info \n61:     - [ ] Communicated on PR detailed description of changes made, and rationale. Include checklists.\n62: \n63: If the user intent is not clear, or you are not confident to make changes, you should stop work, report back to the user, including any questions in the issue.\n64: \n65: Otherwise, if you proceed to making and committing changes, include the checklist in the comments you communicate to the PR. Everything should be checked or marked N/A.\n66: \n67: ### PRE-VALIDATION: What to do if the ontology is invalid BEFORE you commence work.\n68: \n69: In general you should ONLY make changes in scope of the issue. However, if validation fails\n70: BEFORE you start work, and this requires a minor fix, go ahead and make it.\n71: \n72: Otherwise you should not make edits, and end after communicating back on the original issue with\n73: a detailed description of what is invalid, and a plan for how to fix things.\n74: \n75: ## RESEARCH [see also: /research skill]\n76: \n77: You can do searches for literature using web search tools. For focused deep research, you can use `deep-research-client`.\n78: \n79: Use PMIDs where possible, and ALWAYS check that these PMIDs are the correct ones, and not typos or hallucinated.\n80: \n81: Never fabricate PMIDs or other reference IDs, always use /research to produce a RESEARCH.md file which you can copy from.\n82: \n83: ## TERM-SEARCH: Search and lookup of GO terms\n84: \n85: You should always find relevant terms in the ontology before starting work.\n86: \n87: The recommended way to find terms in `src/ontology/go-edit.obo` is using `obo-grep.pl`\n88: \n89: - To look at a specific term if you know the ID:\n90:     - `obo-grep.pl --noheader -r 'id: GO:0004177' src/ontology/go-edit.obo`\n91: - All mentions of an ID\n92:     - `obo-grep.pl --noheader -r 'GO:0004177' src/ontology/go-edit.obo`\n93: - Regexes; all mentions of hand (in any part of the stanza)\n94:     - `obo-grep.pl --noheader -r 'hand' src/ontology/go-edit.obo`\n95: - Regexes; all mentions of hand or foot:\n96:     - `obo-grep.pl --noheader -r '(hand|foot)' src/ontology/go-edit.obo`\n97: - Regexes; all mentions of hand or foot in the definition line:\n98:     - `obo-grep.pl --noheader -r 'def: \".*(hand|foot)' src/ontology/go-edit.obo`\n99: - Note that `obo-grep.pl` is in your PATH, no need to search for it    \n100: - Only search over `src/ontology/go-edit.obo`\n101: \n102: Troubleshooting: if you can't find `go-edit.obo` it likely means you have changed folder, navigate back up to where the repo is checked out\n103: \n104: ### Searching terms in other ontologies\n105: \n106: Use the /external-term-lookup skill if you need to find non-GO terms.\n107: \n108: ## DESIGN-PATTERNS: consult documented patterns for categories of ontology terms\n109: \n110: This ontology includes many design patterns for different categories of term. If your plan involves making non-trivial edits then\n111: you must use the /design-pattern skill to research what design patterns exist for terms to be edited.\n112: \n113: ### EDITS: creating changes to be checked into the edit obo file\n114: \n115: The source file for this ontology is `src/ontology/go-edit.obo`. Generally editing should follow a \"checkin\" and \"checkout\" procedure (note: NOT the same as git checkin/out) to facilitate working with small term-specific files, rather than a megafile which is hard to fit into context.\n116: \n117: The general procedure is:\n118: \n119: * Find relevant terms with `obo-grep.pl`\n120: * Checkout terms with `obo-checkout.pl`\n121: * Make edits in terms/\n122: * Checkin terms with `obo-checkin.pl`\n123: * Perform ontology-wide validation\n124: \n125: - IMPORTANT: Do not edit the edit file directly, it's large\n126: - Add edits should be made in the `terms/` folder\n127: - check out a term into `terms/`: `obo-checkout.pl src/ontology/go-edit.obo GO:1234567 [OTHER IDS]`\n128: - This will create a single stanza obo files `terms/go_1234567.obo` which you can easily edit\n129:      - (note the colon is replaced with an underscore)\n130: - You can go ahead and edit the smallers files in the `terms/` folder\n131: - After edits, check back in: `obo-checkin.pl src/ontology/go-edit.obo GO:1234567 [OTHER IDS]`\n132: - if you like you can edit multiple terms in one batch, e.g. `terms/my_batch.obo`\n133:      - `obo-checkout.pl src/ontology/go-edit.obo terms/my_batch.obo`\n134:      - <make edits to terms/my_batch.obo>\n135:      - `obo-checkin.pl src/ontology/go-edit.obo terms/my_batch.obo`\n136: - checking in will update the edit file and remove the file from `terms/`\n137: - Commits are then made on src/ontology/go-edit.obo as appropriate\n138: - Note that `obo-checkout.pl` and `obo-checkin.pl` are in your PATH, no need to search for it    \n139: - Always validate after checkin via `cd src/ontology && make travis_build`\n140: \n141: ### Creation of new terms\n142: \n143: Always follow this procedure:\n144: \n145: * Work on new terms in a file in the top level `terms/` folder\n146: * New terms start  GO:777xxxx\n147:    - Do do `grep id: GO:777 src/ontology/go-edit.obo` to check for clashes (in ids and alt_ids)\n148:    - Make a file `terms/GO_777xxxx.obo` with a fresh stanza\n149: * Place this in the edit file with `obo-checkin.pl src/ontology/go-edit.obo terms/GO_777xxxx.obo`\n150: \n151: Please do not try and place new terms in the edit file directly as they may end up in the wrong place.\n152: \n153: ### OBO Format Guidelines\n154: \n155: - Term ID format: GO:NNNNNNN (7-digit number)\n156: - Each term requires: id, name, namespace, definition with references\n157: - Never guess GO IDs, use search tools above to determine actual term\n158: - Never guess PMIDs for references, do a web search if needed\n159: - Use standard relationship types: is_a, part_of, has_part, etc.\n160: - Follow existing term patterns for consistency\n161: \n162: Tip: It's always a good idea to look at the structure of existing similar terms, these can be found with `obo-grep.pl`\n163: \n164: ## RELATIONSHIPS: logical axioms and conforming to design patterns\n165: \n166: All terms should have at least one `is_a` (this can be implicit by a logical definition, see below).\n167: It's common for BP and CC terms to have a `part_of` relationship. `regulates` relations are used for regulation terms.\n168: In the edit file, all relationship types are specified using the \"short form\" and not the RO/BFO ID.\n169: \n170: Logical definitions should be included if the term is compositional in nature, and there is a design pattern. Logical definitions should follow genus-differentia form, and the text definition should mirror the logical definition. \n171:  \n172:  Here \"logical definitions\" means necessary AND SUFFICIENT conditions, expressed in obo format using `intersection_of` tags, which map to OWL equivalence axioms. E.g.\n173: \n174:  ```obo\n175:  id: T\n176:  intersection_of: G ! <genus term>\n177:  intersection_of: R D ! <differentia>\n178:  ```\n179:  <=>\n180:  ```owl\n181:  R EquivalentTo (G and R some D)\n182:  ```\n183: \n184:  Example:\n185: \n186: ```\n187: [Term]\n188: id: GO:0001649\n189: name: osteoblast differentiation\n190: namespace: biological_process\n191: def: \"The process whereby a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of an osteoblast, a mesodermal or neural crest cell that gives rise to bone.\" [CL:0000062]\n192: synonym: \"osteoblast cell differentiation\" EXACT []\n193: intersection_of: GO:0030154 ! cell differentiation\n194: intersection_of: results_in_acquisition_of_features_of CL:0000062 ! osteoblast\n195: relationship: part_of GO:0001503 ! ossification\n196: ```\n197: \n198: Here the genus is `cell differentiation` and the differentia points to a CL term. Never guess these IDs, use tools to find them.\n199: Never guess the pattern or relationships. Consult the design pattern docs or look for similar terms (e.g. other differentiation terms).\n200: These are necessary and sufficient conditions, so if there is another term for differentiation of a more specific kind of osteoblast, it will be classified here.\n201: \n202: The reasoner can find the most specific `is_a`, so it's OK to leave this off. The edit file is in \"pre-reasoned\" state. Similarly, it's generally an anti-pattern to have more than one asserted `is_a`.\n203: \n204: Always make sure that design patterns are conformed to, especially for compositional terms. Use the /design-pattern skill to check for conformance of name, def and logical def.\n205: \n206: But also use prior art: look for similar terms with `obo-grep.pl`\n207: \n208: IMPORTANT: logical definitions should map to the text definition and label, and should specify BOTH necessary AND SUFFICIENT conditions.\n209: It may be tempting to use the `intersection_of` construct for expressing links to external ontology terms, but it's fine to simply use `relationship` tags!\n210: \n211: A common anti-pattern is using logical definitions where relationships suffice. This is over-specification. For example:\n212: \n213: ```\n214: !! Example of an INCORRECT axiomatization\n215: name: keratinization\n216: def: \"The process in which the cytoplasm of the outermost cells of the vertebrate epidermis is replaced by keratin. Keratinization occurs in the stratum corneum, feathers, hair, claws, nails, hooves, and horns.\" [GOC:dph, GOC:ebc, GOC:sdb_2009, GOC:tb]\n217: intersection_of: GO:0032501 ! multicellular organismal process ### WRONG\n218: intersection_of: occurs_in CL:0000362 ! epidermal cell         ### WRONG\n219: ```\n220: \n221: The above is completely wrong. The formal reason that there are OTHER kinds of multicellular organismal processes that occur in epidermal cells that are NOT keratinizations. It might help to think of this in OWL terms, as saying kerarinization is the same as the intersection of MOPs that occurs_in some epidermal cell. Other red flags are:\n222: \n223: 1. This does not correspond to a design pattern\n224: 2. The label does to map to the logical definition (a label for this logical definition would be something like \"epidermal multicellular process\")\n225: 3. The text definition does not map to the logical definition (a text def for this logical definition would be something like \"Any MOP that occurs in an epidermal cell\")\n226: \n227: In this case it is perfectly fine to have weaker axiomatization:\n228: \n229: ```\n230: !! Example of an CORRECT weaker axiomatization\n231: name: keratinization\n232: def: \"The process in which the cytoplasm of the outermost cells of the vertebrate epidermis is replaced by keratin. Keratinization occurs in the stratum corneum, feathers, hair, claws, nails, hooves, and horns.\" [GOC:dph, GOC:ebc, GOC:sdb_2009, GOC:tb]\n233: is_a: GO:0032501 ! multicellular organismal process ### CORRECT\n234: relationship: occurs_in CL:0000362 ! epidermal cell ### CORRECT\n235: ```\n236: \n237: An example of when stronger axiomatization is warranted:\n238: \n239: ```\n240: id: GO:0032042\n241: name: mitochondrial DNA metabolic process\n242: namespace: biological_process\n243: def: \"The chemical reactions and pathways involving mitochondrial DNA.\" [GOC:mah]\n244: synonym: \"mitochondrial DNA metabolism\" EXACT []\n245: synonym: \"mtDNA metabolic process\" EXACT []\n246: synonym: \"mtDNA metabolism\" EXACT []\n247: intersection_of: GO:0006259 ! DNA metabolic process\n248: intersection_of: occurs_in GO:0005739 ! mitochondrion\n249: ```\n250: \n251: Here the DP, label (and synonyms), text def, logical def all align, and the OWL axiomatization is trivially true.\n252:  \n253: \n254: ## METADATA\n255: \n256: - ALWAYS include created_by and creation_date for terms YOU CREATE\n257: - NEVER add or modify these properties if you are simply editing an existing term\n258: - Unlike other obo ontologies, there is always a `namespace:` tag in GO (including on obsolete terms)\n259: - Link back to the issue you are dealing with using the `term_tracker_item`\n260: - All terms should have definitions, with at least one definition xref, ideally a PMID\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 429. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# GO Ontology Project Guide\n\nThis includes instructions for editing the go ontology and related files in response to GitHub issues.\n\n## Project Layout\n\nThe project follows standard ODK layout:\n\n * src\n    * ontology/\n       * go-edit.obo\n       * Makefile\n       * ...\n    * taxon_constraints/\n       * only_in_taxon.tsv\n       * never_in_taxon.tsv\n * terms/   ## checked out copies, for editing\n    * GO_NNNNNNN.obo # checked out local copy\n * .claude/\n    * skills/   ## specific skill instructions","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"AGENTS.md","time":{"start":1778981194195,"end":1778981194246}},"id":"prt_e338ac9cc001EabZhYd1yMNv8t","sessionID":"ses_1cc754bd9ffeuD9IYi2ivYftXO","messageID":"msg_e338ab55e001VVqszbXzDZNc9l"}}
